<br>
    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#000000">Strategy</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">Bid 0 or 1, as it&#39;s not really important to go 1st or 2nd.  Given the choice, I usually go 2nd to avoid the Ford of Bruinen.<br>
<br>
Free peoples is able to cope with pretty much anything.  Armor neutralises the Balrog, Cave Troll, and Uruks.  Most Nazgul are chopped into small pieces once you get Aragorn and Boromir equipped with 2 flaming brands each, and the dagger strikes are usable by all 4 companions.<br>
Don&#39;t be afraid to take wounds, as there&#39;s loads of healing in the deck.<br>
Against the swarm, there&#39;s Aragorn&#39;s Bow to reduce the numbers, as well as PATHS and Valiant Man of the West.  Sting, the No Strangers and Talent help keep the twilight low.<br>
I like to double move 4-6, and it&#39;s entirely possible with this deck, especially if you have armor and low twilight and your opponent plays the Balrog who can&#39;t follow you :-)<br>
Hopefully, by site 6 you&#39;ll be ahead, and using Thror&#39;s Map to lay down the killing blow at Brown Lands.  <br>
<br>
For the shadow side, don&#39;t worry too much about winning skirmishes, as your minions have already done their damage.  Occasionally, though, you can get a good swarm going and end up stacking quite a few orcs.   </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#000000"> </Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">DeckTech <BR> For the Players, By the Players  <BR>www.decktech.net </FONT></TD></TR></table> 
